ence of Parisians whose lives were touched by the affair. This compulsively readable book brilliantly evokes the texture of life in 1930s Paris. It also makes an important argument about French society and culture while proposing new understandings of crime and social class in the years before World War II.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMurderzFrancezParisvCase studies. 0aParricidezFrancezParisvCase studies. 0aWomen murdererszFrancezParisvBiography. 0aWomenzFrancezParisxSocial conditionsy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094873040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520948730423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520948730/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles